{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569603"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:29:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:29:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22275"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22275"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.02,0.28,0.51,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110488"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15240"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92752"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43764"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110488"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for management of her type two diabetes, which was diagnosed six months ago. Her medical history includes stage four chronic kidney disease. She does not take any regular medications except for oral hypoglycaemic agents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer most recent blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 95 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular volume 92 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate 25 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHbA1c 7.2% (53 mmol/mol)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most significant reason why HbA1c may be unreliable for monitoring glycaemic control?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced insulin clearance","Altered hepatic glucose production","Impaired renal glucose reabsorption","Increased red blood cell turnover","Increased glycation of plasma proteins"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has stage four chronic kidney disease (CKD) with anaemia. These factors significantly impact the reliability of HbA1c as a measure of glycaemic control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased red blood cell turnover\u003C/strong\u003E is the most significant reason for HbA1c unreliability in this patient. In CKD, uraemic toxins damage red cell membranes, there is increased mechanical fragility, and oxidative stress accelerates red cell destruction. This shortened red cell survival means haemoglobin has less time to become glycated, potentially resulting in falsely low HbA1c values that underestimate true average glucose levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced insulin clearance\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in CKD and can affect glycaemic control, but does not directly impact the relationship between blood glucose and HbA1c. While it may lead to hypoglycaemia in patients on insulin or insulin secretagogues, this does not affect HbA1c reliability as a marker of average glucose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAltered hepatic glucose production\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in advanced CKD due to insulin resistance, but this affects actual glucose levels rather than the relationship between glucose and HbA1c. If hepatic glucose production increases, blood glucose levels would rise, and this would be reflected in the HbA1c.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired renal glucose reabsorption\u003C/strong\u003E becomes significant in advanced CKD but primarily affects glucose handling rather than the HbA1c measurement itself. While this might lead to glycosuria at lower blood glucose levels, it does not directly impact haemoglobin glycation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased glycation of plasma proteins\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in uraemia, but would affect glycated albumin and fructosamine measurements rather than HbA1c. Carbamylation of haemoglobin in uraemia can interfere with some HbA1c assays, but this would cause falsely elevated rather than reduced values.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["HbA1c is unreliable in chronic kidney disease due to reduced red cell lifespan, carbamylation of haemoglobin, and altered erythropoiesis.","Anaemia in chronic kidney disease further complicates HbA1c interpretation due to increased proportion of young red blood cells.","Alternative glycaemic monitoring methods such as continuous glucose monitoring or glycated albumin may be more appropriate in chronic kidney disease."],"references":["Bloomgarden Z, Handelsman Y. How does CKD affect HbA1c? J Diabetes. 2018 Apr;10(4):270. doi: 10.1111/1753-0407.12624. Epub 2017 Dec 21. PMID: 29124865.","Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from:\u00a0https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92752"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22275"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92752"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-31T14:43:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-31T14:43:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15240"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110488"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading